article.headline: Bird scores season-high 27 for Storm
article.linkText: Leslie, Dixon combine for 44 points to lead Sparks
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lisa Leslie made a vow.

"We promise you we're not going to lose again at Staples Center
-- that's a guarantee," Leslie said.

Leslie helped the Sparks snap a two-game home losing streak
Saturday night, scoring 23 points and grabbing 12 rebounds in an
84-75 win over the Seattle Storm.

Seattle was a 69-67 winner when the teams last met on June 19,
but the Storm only led once, 3-0, in Saturday's meeting.

The Sparks (13-3) led 47-34 at halftime and 60-37 with 17:02 to
play.

"We just didn't come out ready to play at all," said Storm
guard Sue Bird, who scored a season-high 27 points.

All five Sparks starters finished in double figures. Tamecka
Dixon scored 21 points before leaving the game with 1:42 to play
after aggravating a sore right knee in a collision. DeLisha Milton
had 15, Mwadi Mabika added 13 and Nikki Teasley scored 12.

"I thought we did a good job from start to finish, really
sharing the ball," Leslie said.

Los Angeles made six of its first seven shots and shot 56
percent from the field in the first half. Then, early in the
second, Teasley's back-to-back 3-point baskets capped an 11-0 run
and gave the Sparks their game-high 23-point lead.

Seattle (9-7) went on a 14-3 run that made it 72-61 with 7:53
remaining, but the Storm could get no closer than nine.

"We expected them to make a run," Leslie said. "They're a
team and they're not going to lay down. This was a good time to put
together some runs as we did. They made a good run, no doubt, but
we got our composure and we were able to come back and make some
baskets."

Jackson, the WNBA's leading scorer at 19.7 points per game,
finished with 19 on 6-of-16 shooting. Kamila Vodichkova added 17
for Seattle.
